{
    "analysis": "Previous steps completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, anomaly detection, and strict fault-interval selection. After filtering for sustained and significant breaches, only one high-confidence metric-level fault candidate remained: IG01 OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio during 2021-03-07 08:08:00 — 08:09:00 (UTC+8), a 2-minute interval with severity ≈1.55 (peak ≈55% above global p95). This suggests an I/O-wait spike on IG01 that may have impacted request handling. To localize the root cause component and exact occurrence time and reason, we must follow the diagnostics order: metric analysis → trace analysis → log analysis. The next logical step is trace analysis for IG01 around the detected fault interval to see if IG01 shows concurrent trace latency increases or downstream service impact (trace.duration* or trace.to_* row_count drops) at 08:08–08:09. If IG01 trace durations or its downstream call durations spike at that time, IG01 is very likely the root cause and the reason is I/O wait (i.e., high disk I/O read usage). If traces do not show correlation, we must expand the search window and inspect other resources and logs.\n\nWhat has been done: metric-level fault-intervals were filtered with strict criteria; IG01 CPU Wio fault identified at 08:08–08:09. What can be derived next: trace evidence that corroborates IG01 being the root cause by showing increased trace durations or row_count drops at the same timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the previously computed global p95 values (compute global p95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) from the full trace.csv series if not already available), filter trace records to component IG01 and to the incident window 2021-03-07 08:00:00 — 08:30:00 UTC+8. From those IG01 records, return rows (limit 50) where the trace value at any timestamp within the window meets one of these: value >= global_p95 (for duration/latency metrics) OR value <= global_p05 (for row_count/throughput metrics). For each returned row include: timestamp, trace_name, value, global_p95, global_p05, severity_ratio (for high-is-bad: value/global_p95; for low-is-bad: global_p05/value). Also return a compact summary: total number of IG01 trace-anomalous points in-window, earliest anomalous timestamp for IG01, and a list of unique downstream targets referenced in trace_name (e.g., to_Tomcat01, to_Tomcat02, etc.). Limit returned anomalous rows to top 50 sorted by severity_ratio descending. Store the full IG01-in-window trace table in kernel variable ig01_traces_window for follow-up but only print the compact anomaly rows and the small summary."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor run inspected IG01 traces in-window and returned 31 anomalous trace points (earliest at 2021-03-07 08:00:00 UTC+8). The highest-severity trace anomalies are latency spikes from IG01 → Tomcat03 around 08:15 (trace.to_Tomcat03.duration_mean ≈1.64s, ~2.05× global p95; trace.to_Tomcat03.duration_p95 ≈3.66s, ~1.54× p95). Earlier, metric-level strict filtering identified a single high-confidence metric fault: IG01 OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio for 2021-03-07 08:08:00—08:09:00 (2 minutes, severity ≈1.55). What has been done: global thresholds were computed on full series, metric anomalies were detected, strict fault-interval filtering returned IG01 CPU Wio as the only high-confidence metric fault, and IG01 trace anomalies were enumerated (notably 08:15 latencies toward Tomcat03). What can be derived: IG01 shows both a short IO-wait spike at ~08:08 and significant trace latency toward Tomcat03 at ~08:15. To localize the root cause we need to verify if IG01 has additional metric anomalies coincident with the trace spikes (especially around 08:15) or if the IO-wait at 08:08 precedes downstream latency at 08:15. Also check logs on Tomcat03 (and other Tomcats) around 08:15 for correlated errors or throughput drops. Since we currently have only one metric-level strict fault (IG01 CPU Wio), the working hypothesis is that IG01 is the root cause, but traces point to downstream latency at 08:15; we must confirm correlation via IG01 metrics across the window and Tomcat logs/metrics at 08:15. No error_log entries were present in-window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze IG01 metric series in the incident window to find any other metric anomalies that correlate with the IG01 trace latency spikes (especially around 08:15) or the earlier IO-wait spike (08:08–08:09). Using the full metric.csv compute global p95 and p05 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) first (do NOT compute thresholds after filtering). Then filter metric.csv to cmdb_id == 'IG01' and time window 2021-03-07 08:00:00 — 08:30:00 UTC+8. For each IG01 metric point in-window flag anomaly if: (a) KPI name looks like high-is-bad (contains any of 'duration','CPU','Memory','Heap','Threads','Load','Wio','SysTime','UserTime','gc_pause','OOM','MaxTime','MaxThreads') and value >= global_p95; OR (b) KPI name looks like low-is-bad throughput (contains 'row_count','rows','throughput') and value <= global_p05; OR (c) log.error_count > 0. Return a compact table (limit 50 rows) of IG01 anomalous points sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: timestamp, kpi_name, value, global_p95, global_p05, severity_ratio, and a one-line note if the timestamp is within 08:06–08:10 or 08:13–08:17 (to highlight proximity to the 08:08 IO-wait and 08:15 trace spikes). Also return a small summary: total IG01 anomalous points in-window, earliest anomaly timestamp, list of unique IG01 KPIs that were anomalous, and whether any anomaly occurs at 08:15 exactly. Store the full IG01-in-window metric table in kernel variable ig01_metrics_window for follow-up but only print the compact anomaly rows and the summary."
